feedback: The first time through, I really didn't have a clue what was going on so when it came to figuring out which family the pattern belonged to, it was all guessing.  On the 2nd run through when the pattern-family association changed, it dawned on me to keep track of how many times each pattern appeared in which family, and then used that information to guess which pattern belonged to which family more often and selected the one with the higher chance.
The first test the features seemed to match up to the corresponding number (1 feature = #1, 2 or more features = #2). The second test seemed to be the opposite.
one side had more of the pairs and the other side had most of the single ones and vice versa
I tried to figure out when certain circles would match with a certain family. The first task was easier to do then the second where I didn't see any kind of pattern
I tried to remember what is the average repitition and pattern for one number or keeping an imaging memory.

It seemed to me that one of the families had all 3 of the characteristics more often than the other on each trial, but then it seemed like there was no real pattern either, so it was a bit frustrating.
A single circle was usually designated a certain family, regardless of placement, whereas multiple circles were automatically assigned to the other family.
It seemed as if the rules for the figures changed from the first set to the second set
I tried to get a picture of what features are most common in what categories and the overall picture or shape of the rectangle with different circles to assign to each category.
based on the examples i was given
I tried to find common patterns within each family such as 3 figures usually related to 1 family.  Singles usually belonged to another.
I looked at the number of features each images had, Single features was one category and multiple features were the second.

I could only work with consistency because the features periodically bled over between Family 1 and Family 2.  The only consistency (more often than not) I saw was that in the first trial Family 1 had one dot in the box while Family 2 had 2 and 3 dots in the box.  Conversely, in trial 2 Family 1 had 2 and 3 dots in the box while Family 2 had one dot in the box.
first many circles were in the 2 family then only on circle in the 2 amily

I just tried to remember the placement and pattern of each family before starting.  It was easiest for me to remember the three solids or both ends, or a single middle one, and I tried to remember those first.

I just clued in on my initial strategy which was to find correlation between a family and the frequency of one.  Once I recognized a significant correlation I used prior knowledge from the scenario and continued counting total instances of two or three features.  After fifty trials, I counted 8 instances of two features and 1 instance of three features.  From this, I reasoned that I could be ~80% correct if I chose only one feature shown to belong to that family every time.
I didn't use any strategies
i had no idea what the pattern was, I thought the items with 1 feature would be from family 1 but that was not the case, so i mainly guessed
On the first one I had an idea of what combo went with which family and tried to make decisions on that but in the second I wasn't sure and I guessed more often than not.
I just tried my best to look for a pattern; although most times there was none.
I was unable to decipher any meaningful pattern from either experiment.
I went slowly initially and tried to see if any patterns emerged. When I had a general idea, I clicked through quickly to see if the pattern was confirmed.
I sort of felt that pieces were more likely to be associated with the opposite family (shapes on the left with family 2), but it was a very vague connection
I tried to remember singles and doubles and their association with the groupings as best as I could.

I looked at how often the features appeared in each family and then tried to select the corresponding family most of the time.  Sometimes I would switch depending on what I thought the percentage was of the other family being a possibility.  It seemed like in the first trial three features were more common in family 2 and one feature was more common in family 1.  Two features seemed more divided.  The reverse was true in the second trial.
